§ 13 symbolism of sentential calculus; truth functions, and truth tables

Fundamental truth tables

p   q   p ∧ q   p ∨ q   p → q   p = q

T   T     T        T       T       T
T   F     F        T       F       F
F   T     F        T       T       F
F   F     F        F       T       T

(p ∨ q) → (p ∧ r)

p   q   r   p ∨ q   p ∧ r   (p ∨ q) → (p ∧ r)

T   T   T     T        T              T
F   T   T     T        F              F
T   F   T     T        T              T
F   F   T     F        F              T
T   T   F     T        F              F
F   T   F     T        F              F
T   F   F     T        F              F
F   F   F     F        F              T

TTs for the laws of sentential calculus

Law of simplification  (p ∧ q) → p       (∧e1)
p   q   p ∧ q   (p ∧ q) → p
T   T     T              T
F   T     F              T
T   F     F              T
F   F     F              T

Law of contradiction     ¬ [p ∧ (¬p)]
p   ¬p      p ∧ (¬p)    ¬ [p ∧ (¬p)]
T   F         F               T
F   T         F               T

Law of excluded middle   p ∨ (¬p)
p   ¬p      p ∨ (¬p)
T   F         T
F   T         T

